To go no further than the first letter of the first book to Atticus (as given in the editions which are not founded on the chronologi· cal sequence), we find that in it the chauces of Cicero in his candi- dature for the consulship are fully discussed. We pursue our reading till we come to the tenth letter of the same book, when we again find Cicero anxious about an election. Will not the ‚render naturally suppose this to be the election spoken of in the first letter Ρ But no; in the tenth letter Cicero is discussing his election to the praetorship, which he held two years before he had written the letter which stands in the ordinary editions as the first letter of the first book to Atticus.
